WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:08.000
So, we're here to talk about how at our biotech Denali we adopted R and mainly leveraged Posit.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Well, just a little introduction. I'm Nicole Jones. I'm a senior data scientist at Denali Therapeutics.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.000
There I wear many hats. I'm a study lead. I'm an R package validation lead.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:23.000
I am a Shiny developer, and I'm a newly minted Posit admin.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:30.000
So, just a disclaimer, all these views in this presentation are my own and do not reflect the views of my company.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:32.000
So, now let's actually get into the talk.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:38.000
So, I'm going to share with us first the journey to Posit and what brought me to this stage today.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:43.000
So, when Denali got started, we were a house, a shop of R programmers.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:51.000
We did our internal exploratory analysis in R, and anytime we needed to do regulatory work, we would go to CRO and do it in SAS.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:55.000
We didn't love that. We're R programmers. We wanted to leverage R.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:02.000
So, when I joined, one of the first things we laid out was what did we want our workflows and our programming life to look like.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.000
First, we wanted to be able to support internal R-based filing.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:12.000
We needed a GXP compliant system that would allow us to do this R-based filing and support our workflows.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:17.000
And we all know the famous, hey, it worked on my machine, but it didn't work on your machine.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:22.000
So, we wanted a shared R environment to make sure we didn't have those situations.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:28.000
So, we found a statistical vendor to give us a statistical computing environment, but it was really designed for SAS.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.000
So, we worked alongside them to kind of come up with a solution for R.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:35.000
And this is what the solution looked like.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:38.000
This is the editor inside of our statistical computing environment.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:43.000
You don't have any of the features and the bells and whistles we know and love with RStudio.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:52.000
This is not an interactive session, so when you run your code and our server gets spun up on the back end, it executes the code, it gets killed.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:55.000
And then you have to go look at the outputs and things like that.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:57.000
We didn't love this.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:02.000
We did have the option of using RStudio Desktop to integrate with our SCE,

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:08.000
but then we still had that problem of I could have a different version of R, a different version of packages than my colleagues.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:10.000
So, we didn't want to go that route.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:17.000
So, we knew we wanted a proper editor, a proper development environment, and we did not want these disjointed R environments.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:22.000
And so, that led us to Posit, one thing that could allow us to implement these things.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:29.000
We saw we'd get our familiar RStudio IDE that we know and love with all the interactivity and everything we've come to know.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:32.000
We would have a single R environment across our entire team.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:33.000
We can enable that now.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:36.000
And then there were a couple other added features where we could host packages,

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
internally developed packages straight from GitHub to Posit Package Manager,

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:47.000
and we could host our interactive reports and Shiny apps directly to Posit Connect.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:50.000
So, we saw a lot of benefits, but we also knew that there were going to be some challenges,

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:59.000
so we had to take a pause and really consider what was the scope, what were we agreeing to kind of take on by adopting Posit.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:00.000
We're not a big pharma company.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:05.000
We don't have the big infrastructure and the support that a lot of these other pharma companies had.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:11.000
In fact, it was just if we were going to do this, it was myself and my manager, Thomas, who had to be the people implementing this, right?

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:14.000
So, we had a small team, and that meant we were going to juggle a lot of things.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:18.000
We were going to have to learn a lot of things and wear many, many hats.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:23.000
We had to integrate our SCE with Posit Package Manager, and really not just say integrate, but what does that mean?

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:24.000
What does that look like?

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:26.000
What are the limitations of our SCE?

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:27.000
What are the limitations of Posit?

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:29.000
How are we going to make this happen?

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:30.000
This was not an easy process.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:34.000
This took us a while, many iterations, and even now, we're still working some kinks out.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:39.000
So, definitely start this early and really get down to the granularity of what does this mean,

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:43.000
and how does your data get shared, all these different things.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:49.000
We also wanted to be able, in our Posit Workbench, to support exploratory analyses and regulatory work.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:51.000
We had to work with our QA and IT teams.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:55.000
That added a whole other kink in our process, and we had to modify our workflows.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:04:01.000
Like I said before, our SCE was not originally built for R, and the solution they built had limitations,

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:05.000
and so the typical way code gets processed is a little different inside of our SCE,

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:08.000
and we had to learn and modify these workflows.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:09.000
So, we sat that.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:10.000
We saw our benefits.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:11.000
We saw the challenges.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:13.000
We said, okay, if we're going to do this, we need to come up with a plan.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:16.000
So, we sat down, and we figured out what's our plan.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:22.000
So, outside of this whole Posit system, we had already developed a process for validating our packages.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:28.000
We used a snapshot-based method, pick a snapshot, grab packages from that date, validate a subset,

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.000
and the rest are not validated.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.000
So, we gave our SCE access only to those validated packages.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:39.000
Those are the packages approved for use in our regulatory work, so that's all that our SCE would be able to access.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:46.000
In Posit Workbench, when we're running our programs, we want the same experience that we'd have inside the SCE.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:51.000
So, in our Posit Workbench, we have that same subset of validated packages from that same snapshot,

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:55.000
so we don't have an issue with package versions being out of sync and things working in Posit Workbench

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:57.000
and then breaking inside of our SCE.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:03.000
But, as I said, we want exploratory work in Posit Workbench, so we gave access to our non-validated packages

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:07.000
only inside of Posit Workbench to allow our programmers to still do all the fun things that we do

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:11.000
that are outside of our regulatory work.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:12.000
We had to define our system architecture.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:13.000
What would this look like?

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:19.000
So, we opted to have our vendors host everything within the same environment as our SCE.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Our SCE uses Docker Container as a backer for the R execution,

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.000
and so we had our Docker Container install packages straight from Posit Package Manager.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:32.000
Our Posit Workbench and Posit Connect install from that same Posit Package Manager,

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:36.000
and then we had to define how we were going to share the data across all these systems.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:39.000
So, that was definitely a challenge, and we figured that out.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:44.000
We also didn't want to be limited with our vendors and only allowing them to update things,

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:49.000
so we gave some of our team members admin access and keys, essentially, into the system

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:54.000
so that we can make updates and not face a bottleneck waiting for our vendors to do minor things.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:57.000
And then, finally, in compliance with our QA and IT requirements,

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:00.000
we used our single sign-on method that we use across all our platforms.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Definitely, there's benefits and there's pros and cons to using this method,

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:07.000
but one of the biggest pros is it's the same login we use everywhere.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:10.000
Make it easy, easy to get into the system.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:16.000
And so, we saw benefits, we kind of had a feel for our challenges, we laid out our plan,

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.000
and now it was time to put it into action.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:25.000
So, all this kind of started about seven months into my role now at Denali,

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:31.000
and I get an email, and in this email, it has an IP address, a port, my username, and a password.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:33.000
I say, okay, great, what do I do with this?

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:35.000
And then I get an IM from Thomas, my manager, and he says,

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:41.000
Nicole, can you go into Posit Connect and start enabling things, SSH into the system?

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:46.000
I don't have a background in anything that has to do with anything like that, so this was my reaction.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:48.000
What do you mean SSH into a server?

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:49.000
How do I do that?

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:50.000
Where do I start?

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:51.000
I'm starting to freak out.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:52.000
I'm seven months into my job.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:54.000
I don't want to tell them I don't know how to do something, right?

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:56.000
You know, and I'm just like, take a deep breath.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:58.000
And I say, okay, Thomas, I don't know what you're talking about.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.000
Can we get on a call?

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.000
And a great manager, as he is, he hops on a call, and also, you know,

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:05.000
don't be afraid to say you don't know how to do something.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:06.000
That's the only way you learn.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:10.000
So we get on this call, and he shows me the system putty.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:11.000
Nice and simple.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:12.000
You put in the IP address.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:13.000
You put in the port.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:14.000
Press okay.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:18.000
Next screen, you put in your username, your password, and then you connect.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:23.000
He even showed me, it's not so clear to see, but there's a configuration file in all of these,

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:26.000
in Posit Package Manager, Posit Workbench, and Posit Connect,

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:29.000
where you actually go and make these changes and set certain system settings.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:32.000
So he showed me in Posit Workbench how you get to this.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:35.000
He showed me all the things he had already been playing around with, things he created.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:37.000
And then finally, I'm like, okay, how do you edit this?

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:39.000
And he says, oh, Vim.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:42.000
And if you've ever done a merge on Git, you've worked with Vim.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:45.000
So familiar, right, familiar kind of text editor.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:46.000
I say, okay, great.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:47.000
All right, I can do this, right?

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:48.000
I walk out that call.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:49.000
I'm confident.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:52.000
And I go and I say, okay, it's my turn to get into Posit Connect.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:54.000
He's done what he had to do with Posit Workbench.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:55.000
Let me get to Posit Connect.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:56.000
And I run this command.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:59.000
This is a command that should open the config file.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:01.000
And I get this message.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:02.000
Pseudo not found.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:04.000
And this is my reaction.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:07.000
Because I just got off this call with him.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:08.000
I know I took notes.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:11.000
I don't want to message him again and say, hey, I'm stuck, right?

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:14.000
Because then, like, I'm seven months into my job.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:16.000
Maybe he's going to say I made a mistake, right?

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.000
So anyway, I did some Googling, you know, about 15 minutes later.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:22.000
And I realized I just need to install Vim into the server.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:24.000
Oof, okay, problem solved.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:26.000
So we get Vim installed.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:27.000
And now I'm up and running.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:31.000
So I had essentially two main tasks inside of Connect initially.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:36.000
One, I wanted to enable the deployment of content straight from GitHub to Connect.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:39.000
And then, two, I found this out after when I tried to deploy a Corto document.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:40.000
We also had to enable Corto.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:42.000
So that was another challenge.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:46.000
So to enable content straight from GitHub to Posit Connect,

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:48.000
first I had to work with my IT team.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:49.000
That was a little tricky.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:53.000
Convincing them why we needed this service account and how this would work

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:54.000
and the security vulnerabilities,

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:58.000
it took a few meetings to really get them to understand what it was that I was doing.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:02.000
But once we understood and they were okay with it, we set up a service account.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:05.000
And then inside the config file, this is all you have to add, right?

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:08.000
The only places you need to update are the username and the password.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.000
Everything else would stay the same.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.000
And that's the service account username and then your GitHub PAT

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:15.000
that you generate from that service account.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:18.000
And now anytime we want to deploy anything from GitHub to Connect,

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:22.000
we add this service account as a read-only user to that repository,

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:23.000
and then it can host.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:26.000
This is the preferred method for us for deploying things.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:30.000
It allows you to have constant integration and continuous deployment, right?

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:35.000
You don't have to worry about republishing when you make updates in your main branch.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:39.000
So in Corto, as I said, I went to try to deploy a Corto document and it failed.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:41.000
And so I realized there were a few things.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:44.000
First, we actually have to install Corto on the Linux server.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.000
This is just a snippet of the code.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:49.000
The Posit admin guides have all this well-documented,

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:51.000
so go there if you want to see the full code.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:54.000
But this is just a snippet of the code I had to run inside.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.000
Once I connected to the server, you execute this in the server,

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:59.000
and it installs Corto into the server.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.000
And then inside of the Posit Connect config file,

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.000
we have to enable Corto to allow it to actually be able to host

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:07.000
Corto documents on Posit Connect.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:09.000
And then we were up and running.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:11.000
Until Posit Connect was squared away,

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.000
we kind of set our sights back on Posit Workbench.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:17.000
As I said before, we wanted to ensure our environment was shared

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:20.000
across our development environment and our SCE.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:22.000
We wanted to make sure all the packages were the same.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.000
And so in order to do that, as I mentioned before,

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:28.000
we used a snapshot method for picking and validating our packages

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
that would be put in the SCE.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.000
So we had to do a few things inside of Posit Package Manager

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:34.000
to enable this snapshot.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:37.000
One, this first step is optional, enabling binary package installation.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.000
But if you don't know the difference between non-binary

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:41.000
and binary package installation,

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.000
just know this is much faster and very recommended.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:45.000
So optional, but I say do it.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:47.000
Make sure you know your Linux distribution system.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:48.000
This matters.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.000
If you pick the wrong one, it won't work.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:53.000
So we enabled our binary package installation first.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:55.000
Then the next thing inside of Posit Package Manager,

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:58.000
we enabled snapshot features way down at the bottom by the black box.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.000
You can kind of see it's a little small,

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:03.000
but it ends with the date that you select your packages,

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:08.000
and that is the repos link that we're going to use for installation.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:12.000
The next thing we wanted to do was enable our developers

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.000
to kind of do this easily.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:18.000
So one, we wanted to set our CRAN repo.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:21.000
We wanted to set our default repo to be the Posit Package Manager and not CRAN.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:24.000
And we also wanted to get rid of this GUI piece

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:27.000
that would allow our programmers to change the repo, right,

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:30.000
just to kind of nudge them and guide them in the right direction.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:34.000
So two things we had to do inside of the Posit Workbench configuration file.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:37.000
We had to add the repository link from a couple slides ago

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:39.000
that was blacked out a little bit.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:41.000
We added that repo link here.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:43.000
So now anytime you do install.packages,

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.000
by default it's going to go to that snapshot date

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:47.000
and install packages from there.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:52.000
And then also we disabled the GUI piece.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:55.000
And so now inside of your RStudio,

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:59.000
you won't have that option to interactively select your new repo.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:02.000
Now, of course, if you use install.packages, repos equal.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:05.000
You can always change that. We can't disable that piece.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:08.000
But this is, again, nudging our programmers to do the correct thing

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.000
and kind of keeping them from, you know,

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:12.000
potentially opening themselves up to challenges

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:17.000
that are going to lead to their programs not working as well in the SCE.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:19.000
The next thing we want to do, as I said,

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:22.000
our recommended method of deployment is for Shiny apps

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:26.000
is directly from GitHub to Posit Connect,

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:29.000
not pressing this publish button.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:31.000
The reason for this is if you publish from here,

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.000
it's tied to my account on Posit Connect.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:36.000
And if I win the lottery tomorrow and I decide I don't want to work anymore,

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:39.000
well, now we have to go through a hassle of changing

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.000
who owns that content in Posit Connect.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:44.000
If you deploy straight from GitHub, it's based on the service account.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:49.000
You don't have to worry about any sort of shift, any change in your team.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:51.000
So very simple.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:53.000
Again, inside of Posit Workbench, just add this one line,

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:55.000
allow publish equals zero.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:56.000
It gets rid of that publish button.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.000
And now, again, if you're still using a package,

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:03.000
you can still use the console commands to publish from Posit Workbench.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:06.000
But this is, again, nudging our programmers in the right way

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:09.000
so that they're using our best practices.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:11.000
We had to figure out how to share our data between our SCE

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:12.000
and our Posit Workbench.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:14.000
This was definitely a little bit challenging.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:17.000
And this was, like, one of the final things we worked on

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:18.000
and we have it up and running.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:21.000
It was, again, this is going to be a very unique situation

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:23.000
in how you figure it out for your system,

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:26.000
but we had to work with our vendors to figure that out.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
As I said, we're learning.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:29.000
This process took quite a while.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:32.000
So there are still two things that were kind of under development.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:36.000
Number one, how we're sharing our data between Posit Connect and the SCE.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:40.000
There are some limitations based on our authentication method

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:41.000
that makes it a little challenging,

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:44.000
so we're still kind of working out the best way to do this,

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:48.000
and we've been working closely with our Posit admin team for this.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
So this should be up and running soon.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:54.000
And then also hosting packages from GitHub to Posit Package Manager.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:57.000
Not too difficult to do just with all the things we've had to do,

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:00.000
had to prioritize, so this is coming as well soon.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
But, yeah, that's where we were, right?

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:06.000
So our lessons learned, and this journey was quite a fun journey,

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:09.000
and when we sat back and we looked back at these things,

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:11.000
some of the lessons we learned, which started with, you know,

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:13.000
get familiar with your Posit admin guides.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:15.000
A lot of the times I had a question,

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:18.000
the question was already answered in the Posit admin guides,

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:20.000
so get familiar, look at those.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:22.000
Leverage your Posit support team.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:24.000
They've been an invaluable asset in this whole process.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:28.000
If we had a question, they've done it with so many other organizations,

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
so they can walk you through all the ins and outs, the pros,

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.000
the cons of different methods that you can go about.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
I'd love to say with R, if there's one way to do it,

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
there's 10 other ways to do it.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:37.000
It's the same with this.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.000
There's a lot of times there are different ways you can implement it.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:41.000
It's just based on what works for your system

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:47.000
and what your ITQA will want you to kind of process you'd want to go about.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:48.000
Work closely with your vendors

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:52.000
and really take in their experience with the Posit tool into account.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.000
It took us many iterations to really make sure they understood

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:58.000
what it was we meant when we needed certain features implemented.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:14:59.000
So work with them.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.000
Make sure you're with them every step of the way.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:04.000
And then if you're trying to select vendors,

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.000
if they've set up Posit and worked with Posit before,

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:10.000
definitely make that as part of your decision-making process,

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.000
I would recommend.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:13.000
Start early.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:15.000
It's going to take you much longer than you think.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:17.000
They said we're still working out some of the kinks,

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.000
so don't wait until, hey,

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:21.000
we're going to want to do some reporting event in six months.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:22.000
No, no, no.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:23.000
Start early.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:24.000
It's going to take you much longer.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:28.000
If you see it coming up anytime soon, start your journey as soon as you can.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:29.000
Don't do it alone.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:31.000
There's definitely powers in numbers.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:33.000
For me, it's only two of us, me and Thomas.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:36.000
But if it was just me, I don't know where I'd be right now.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:37.000
I probably wouldn't be on this stage.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:42.000
So definitely have a battle buddy for you, at least one.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:44.000
Don't be afraid to break the system.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:50.000
I did a couple of times, and it got fixed, so don't worry about it.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:52.000
And then the final message is you can do it.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:53.000
We did it.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:54.000
We're doing it.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:55.000
I was just on a call with Thomas this morning.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:58.000
He's running tables and figures and stuff in our system.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.000
Like, it can get done.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
We had a small team, but we did it.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.000
So thank you, and any questions?

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:22.000
So we do have a question from Slido, our virtual audience.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:27.000
If someone wants to update a validated package, how much work is it?

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:31.000
Say they see a nice new feature in a package they want to take advantage of,

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:33.000
how difficult is it to update that package?

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:34.000
Yeah, great question.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:37.000
So that's part of, like, our package validation, like, flow.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:40.000
And, I mean, all in all, really, like, in the grand scheme of things,

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:41.000
not too difficult.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:48.000
But we're just, like, if you're going to request for a package to be updated,

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:52.000
I guess the short answer is we have a process for it.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
I can, in theory, do it in a day.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:57.000
But, like, you know, we have to go through our full QA process

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:58.000
and everything.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:01.000
So I think that just comes down to, like, that question really comes down

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:03.000
to how do you guys handle package validation,

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:06.000
and how often are you guys willing to update your snapshots.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:07.000
Yeah.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:08.000
Great.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:09.000
Yeah, awesome.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:10.000
All right, thank you.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:11.000
Thank you.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:12.000
Thank you.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:13.000
Thank you.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:13.000


